<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870917-0124 </DOCNO><HL> International Corporate Report:Daewoo Plans Second PlantIn Auto Venture With GM</HL><DD> 09/17/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> GMAUTOS, AUTO PARTS (AUT) </IN><TEXT>   Officials of the DAEWOO group said the group plans to add a second assembly plant, with an annual production capacity of 300,000 cars, to its South Korean joint venture with GENERAL MOTORS CORP. of the U.S.    The Korean industrial group and GM each hold 50% of the venture, Daewoo Motor Co., which currently operates an assembly plant in Pupyong, near Seoul.    The officials said the planned plant is expected to begin operation in early 1991. Kunsan, on Korea's west coast, was cited as a possible site for the new plant.    The Daewoo officials didn't elaborate, but the newspaper Maeil Kyungje Shinmun quoted Daewoo's chairman, Kim Woo Joong, as saying that he planned to discuss the project with GM soon.    Daewoo Motor and Korea's two other car assemblers, Hyundai Motor Co. and Kia Motors Corp., export subcompacts mainly to the U.S. </TEXT></DOC>